<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Which measures productive efficiency in an economy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Real GDP</option>
            <option letter="b">Nominal GDP</option>
            <option letter="c">Real GDP per worker</option>
            <option letter="d">Real GDP per capita</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Real GDP per worker measures productive efficiency because it shows how much output is produced per worker, adjusting for inflation and directly measuring labor productivity.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does increased income inequality affect the consumption function?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Shifts it up because wealthy people spend more</option>
            <option letter="b">Shifts it down because wealthy people have lower MPC</option>
            <option letter="c">Makes it steeper</option>
            <option letter="d">Has no effect on consumption function</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Increased income inequality tends to shift the consumption function down because wealthy individuals have a lower marginal propensity to consume than lower-income individuals.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to velocity of money during a financial crisis?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases as people spend more rapidly</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases as people hold more precautionary balances</option>
            <option letter="c">Stays constant despite the crisis</option>
            <option letter="d">Becomes more volatile but averages normal levels</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During a financial crisis, velocity of money typically decreases as people and businesses hold more precautionary money balances and reduce spending, causing money to circulate more slowly.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in the minimum wage affect the SRAS curve?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Shifts SRAS right</option>
            <option letter="b">Shifts SRAS left</option>
            <option letter="c">Moves along the SRAS curve</option>
            <option letter="d">Has no effect on SRAS</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in the minimum wage raises production costs for businesses, causing the Short-Run Aggregate Supply curve to shift left as firms produce less output at each price level.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
